,Not Recommended,253840,32906255,Posted: 27 June,all,NegativeRainbow,"First things first, the music and visuals in this game are fantastic, my issues with this game lie 100% in the gameplay.In this game, unlike previous shantae games, the levels are treated like sonic style stages split into different acts, rather than the more metroidvania style zones in past shantae games. This wouldn't necessarily be a bad thing, as new transformations make replaying levels legitimately interesting at first, but as you play more, the pace of the game starts really falling apart.You gain new transformations after beating the boss of each level, so you're immediately unable to explore your new abilities unless you replay old levels, which you are forced to do because after every level you are handed a fetch quest to get the macguffin to lead to the next level. This gets old very quickly, especially when you have to go back to levels that you've already replayed once before, the warp dance and the whistle only speed this up so much. This gets more extreme when you find that your transformations aren't enough, and it's only after exploring for a while that you find an upgrade for your transformation to help you finish the fetch quest. Exploring on your own is also not very rewarding, because often you either run into a wall where you need a future transformation you don't have yet, or all you've managed to do is find a future macguffin before you were told to. This makes progression feel slow and awkward and ultimately nowhere near as fulfilling as past shantae games.One other nitpick, the pacing in levels is sometimes off too, for example lazers, spikes, and pits won't just damage you, but also teleport you back to the start of a stage, so puzzles full of this obstacles don't just damage you, but also revert so much progress that getting back gets legitimately frustrating. I think if this issue alone was solved, the game overall might be much less frustrating to play through.Overall, if you want to get this game to experience the music and art, and are willing to bear with the poor pacing in gameplay, then go ahead. If not, you might want to pass this one up."
