76561198041756601,Recommended,253840,33564762,Posted: 15 July,all,JiiPee,"Shortly:4th Shantae game that continues the story further., however Shantae: Half-Genie Hero is quite different from its predecessors.First recognisable difference is how the game looks. Unlike the pixxelated art style in the previous Shantae games, this time the game has this more cartoonish art style which isn't half bad. The character movements and the world feels more alive.That leads to the 2nd noticable difference, which is the world itself. In the previous games, you had this semi-open world that you could explore once you obtained powers to do so. There's no such thing in the Half-Genie Hero, but instead the world is diveded into stages/worlds. Each stage/world has several areas lined after each other that you can explore and at the end of each world there's a boss waiting for you. Once you defeat that, the world is cleared and you can move on to next one. Its kinda similar to how the islands worked in the Pirate's Curse, but this time they have this ""super mario"" feeling in them. It's just not the same as it was in the previous Shantae games, which is kinda disappointing for me. I would have preferred the semi-open world like the Risky's Revenge had.Unlike in the previous Shantae games, the Half-Genie Hero doesn't have any dungeons either, which is mostly because of how those stages/worlds wokr that I mentioned earlier.Other than that, the game is pretty much the same old Shantae games that we're used to.Pros:+ Improved art style+ Familiar gameplay mechanics with few additions mixed in+ Entertaining 2D platformer+ Bigger variety of different abilitiesCons:- Semi-open world replaced with stages/worlds- No dungeons- Save points way too often, which means that dying is no longer punishing as the game asks you every 2-3 minutes if you want to save your progress  (why couldn't they just implement auto save instead if they didn't want people to feel punished for dying, though personally I hate auto saves if they save your progress like that )- The Soundtrack isn't as good as it is in the previous titles - The OST is similar but too...modern.. if you could call it that. Didn't enjoy it personallyDo I recommend?Yes. Shantae: Half-Genie Hero is entertaining 2D platformer and it continues the story where the Pirate's Curse left on. I have to warn you though, the game is not as good as its predecessors are, because of the stage/world system.Verdict:  6.5 / 10 - Good game  (though not as good as its predecessors are because of the stage system)"
