76561198050405832,Recommended,253840,33199023,Posted: 3 July,all,TonyZeCorny,"If you're familiar with the previous Shantae games, you'll definitely feel right at home with this one.It's basically Shantae's first big screen experience. All the familiar characters are back, including a few new ones to keep the story fresh. The gameplay is back to basic; with the transformations being the main focus of travelling through the different levels to find hidden items or NPCs you need to talk to. Need I mention, the soundtrack is as great as ever! I find myself tapping Jake Kaufman's slick beats every time I hear the different themes of the levels and even some of the characters themes. The bosses are huge in scale this time, almost covering the entire screen. Overall, the game is pretty quirky its in character interractions/dialogues and man-- gotta love those vibrant colors!The only downsides I can point out are the amount of backtracking you have to do, considering there's only a handful of levels. Normally, I don't backtracking an issue in Metroidvania-styled games, but the levels are way too short to have any sort of backtracking, only to find NPCs you need to talk so that they can give you an item to progress the story further. If the levels were bigger, I would've forgiven it, but I personally find it very tedious to go back to the same levels over and over again just to make sure you haven't missed a single thing. About the transformations; like I said, the level structure relies too much on them. It's much easier to travel once you obtained all of Shantae's transformations, but then again, it feels very tacky having to transform every second just to be able to land on that one platform you normally can't reach.On a side note, it's not much of a criticism, but I just find it funny that the game is aware that their audience is very ""niche"". There always been hints of innuendos in the character dialogues or how the girl characters are skimpily dressed. It's easy for feminists to tear appart how the game portrays the women. But I think it's not worth judging a simple yet fun game like this that doesn't really offend anybody. It is what it is and I think it's great to have more female leads in gaming.Alright, I'm done rambling for now. I definitely recommend giving a try this short and sweet game that I'm sure you'll enjoy, especially if you're craving for more Metroidvania-styled games... and with a kickass soundtrack on top of that!"
