76561198051264306,Recommended,253840,35503406,Posted: 5 October,all,TheHamBro,"Another great entry for the Shantae series, and just like the previous entries before it, it changes things up a bit from game to game.  The formula is different this time around, but the same Shantae feel is there more than ever.The Good:As always, the music is fantastic.  In fact, I would go as far to say that this is the best soundtrack in the series.  Absolutely phenomenal.  And of course, it wouldn't be Shantae without the humor as I've found myself laughing at it's silliness.  Although I'm a sucker for pixel graphics, the change to a semi 3D/2D cel shaded graphic art style was very pleasing to the eye.  Its colorful, and alot of detail was put into character, level design, and animation.  Everything felt smooth.This is where WayForward changes things up a bit with the formula, Half-Genie Hero insteads goes the route of something akin to Mega Man, where this time you play through a level and less of the Metroidvania layout.  Now, I will always prefer the Metroidvania approach for this series, however despite the change to it's structure, it's still very much a solid platformer and I did not mind the change at all.One gripe I've always had with the Shantae series was it's difficulty, in that every game was on the Easy side.  The initial reviews for this game all seem to point towards the same issue at release.  I firmly believe the best way to play this game is on Hard mode.  Yes, it was frustrating at first, and yes I died a lot.  But it was incredibly challenging when it came to platforming and bosses.  Magic and the animal transformations where crucial for me to survive.   However, the more upgrades you get/find, it does mitigate the difficulty later on so Hard mode doesn't stay frustrating for long.The Not So Good:The manner you acquired new dances felt rushed.  Whereas the other games you happened on some fountain/genie/whatever that teaches you a dance, it was absent here.  Is it minor?  Yeah, probably, but I very much missed stumbling on some set piece to get a new dance.You will revisit the same areas again and again to progress the storyline.  For me, this wasn't a huge deal, as I loved going back to listen to the music and appreciate level design.  But for others, I can see this as getting tedious.  There where a couple of quests where I had to farm an item from a certain enemy, and again to me, felt rushed and unimaginative.There are no dungeons/labrynths in this one,  and I very much wished they included them.  Yeah, each level is great and well done, but it doesn't beat stumbling on a labyrnth in the open world.Hard mode, although great, sometimes felt cheap.  Very early on in the game, enemies will one shot you and the enemy placement can be incredibly aggravating.  Sometimes, in order for me to survive through a level, I had to farm for items/hearts/magic jars.  Again, to me, not a big deal but a deal breaker for others.Overall:What a fantastic game, truly a great platformer.  Despite it's flaws, I was willing to overlook them because of the carefully crafted game WayForward put together.  If you are a fan of  sidescroller/platformer/Metroidvania/whatever genre, pick this one up.  I think you'll enjoy it.After playing all of Shantae games, this is how I would rate each series:1) The Pirate's Curse2) Shantae (GBC)3) Half-Genie Hero4) Risky's Revenge"
